---------------------- data bases -------------------------------------
there is no kind that fits all

relational databases = stores data in structured tables with rows and columns - uses SQL structured query language - used when data is higly structured together such as banks wherrelationships between data is important

non - relational databases = noSQL, offers more flexibility - used with less depending data - can be simple like key value pair storing or just documents

queries = the way the server interacts with databases, which the database then sends back data/deleted data , which the server transforms to json and sends to client

raw queries = communicates directly in the database understanding
-- RAW SQL
SELECT \* FROM users;

orm = object relational mappers = a way to write queries in a programming language - communicates by libraries with the database
// ORM (fx Sequelize)
User.findAll();

----------------------------- the big picture / aka backend structure -----------------------
monolithic arhitecture

- most popular
- all components of the application is combined into a single unified codebase

  pros:

- simple to develop and deploy
- eisier to debug -> everything in same place
  Cons:
- messy for big apps
- hard to scale some components

microservice architecture

- application broken down into smaller independent services
- each service handles a specific buisness function fx. authentication, payment...
- communicates by apis so no longer 1 fronend-backend connection through an api
  pros
- good for big enterprice buisness that is scaling

serverless achitecture

- underlying infrastructure is handled by a cloud provider fx. aws lambda
- used by next.js applications

pros:

- good for startsups
- good for rapid prototyping
- or apps with spiky traffic (easy to increase or decrease handable activity)


